1.5 Normalisation: TMM transformation and LOG transformation

library(edgeR)  
## Loading required package: limma
# 1) make a copy of the data set to do log tranformation 
combined_log <- combined 
 
# 2) Determine which columns are the proteins 
# column 1 = SampleID 
# last 17 columns = clinical data 
protein_cols <- 2:(ncol(combined) - 17) 
 
# 3)extract protein matrix and convert to numeric
protein_matrix <- as.matrix(combined[, protein_cols]) 
protein_matrix <- apply(protein_matrix, 2, function(x) as.numeric(as.character(x))) 
 
# 4) Make DGEList and TMM-normalise 
dge <- DGEList(counts = protein_matrix) 
dge <- calcNormFactors(dge, method = "TMM") 
 
# 5) retrieve normalalised CPM-values 
protein_norm <- cpm(dge, normalized.lib.sizes = TRUE) 
 
# 6) replace de protein-columns in the dataset with TMM-normlalized values 
combined_log[, protein_cols] <- protein_norm 
 
# 7) Conduct log2(x+1) transformation
combined_log[, protein_cols] <- lapply(combined_log[, protein_cols], function(x) { 
 log2(x + 1) 
})

#1.6.3 Volcano plots where the pairwise comparisons are made of the different severity groups

library(dplyr)  
library(ggplot2)  
library(ggrepel)
library(purrr)  
 
# 1. Filter NEGATIVE and set severity levels  
df <- combined_log %>%  
filter(WHO_temp_severity != "NEGATIVE") %>%  
mutate(WHO_temp_severity = factor(WHO_temp_severity,  
                                  levels = c("mild","moderate","severe","critical")))  
 
# 2. Select protein columns 
protein_cols <- 2:(ncol(df) - 16)  
protein_data <- as.data.frame(lapply(df[, protein_cols], function(x) suppressWarnings(as.numeric(x))))  
 
# drop columns who are completely NA or have no variation
protein_data <- protein_data[, colSums(is.na(protein_data)) < nrow(protein_data)]  
protein_data <- protein_data[, apply(protein_data, 2, function(x) length(unique(x[!is.na(x)])) > 1)]  
 
group <- df$WHO_temp_severity  
 
# 3.  Functions for LogFC and P-value  
safe_t_p <- function(x, g1_idx, g2_idx) {  
x1 <- x[g1_idx]; x2 <- x[g2_idx]  
if (sum(!is.na(x1)) < 3 || sum(!is.na(x2)) < 3) return(NA_real_)  
out <- try(t.test(x1, x2)$p.value, silent = TRUE)  
if (inherits(out, "try-error")) return(NA_real_)  
as.numeric(out)  
}  
 
safe_logFC <- function(x, g1_idx, g2_idx) {  
mean(x[g1_idx], na.rm = TRUE) - mean(x[g2_idx], na.rm = TRUE)  
}  
 
# Volcano plot function 
build_volcano <- function(mat, grp, g1, g2) {  
g1_idx <- which(grp == g1)  
g2_idx <- which(grp == g2)  
logFC <- apply(mat, 2, safe_logFC, g1_idx, g2_idx)  
pvals <- apply(mat, 2, safe_t_p, g1_idx, g2_idx)  
res <- tibble(protein = colnames(mat), log2FC = logFC, pvalue = pvals) %>%  
  mutate(adj.P.Val = p.adjust(pvalue, method = "BH"),  
         negLogP = -log10(pvalue),  
         signif = ifelse(adj.P.Val < 0.05 & abs(log2FC) > 1, "Significant", "Not significant"))  
  
p <- ggplot(res, aes(log2FC, negLogP, color = signif)) +  
  geom_point(alpha = 0.8) +  
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Significant" = "#D62728", "Not significant" = "#7F7F7F")) +  
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-1,1), linetype="dashed") +  
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype="dashed") +  
  labs(title = paste("Volcano:", g1, "vs", g2),  
       x = "log2 Fold Change", y = "-log10(p-value)") +  
  theme_minimal()  
  
# Label top 10 hits  
top_hits <- res %>% filter(!is.na(adj.P.Val)) %>% arrange(adj.P.Val) %>% slice_head(n = 10)  
if (nrow(top_hits) > 0) {  
  p <- p + ggrepel::geom_text_repel(data = top_hits, aes(label = protein), size = 3)  
}  
  
print(p)  
return(res)  
}  
 
# 4. All pairwise comparisons 
pairs <- combn(levels(group), 2, simplify = FALSE)  
results_list <- map(pairs, ~build_volcano(protein_data, group, .x[1], .x[2]))  
## Warning: ggrepel: 7 unlabeled data points (too many overlaps). Consider
## increasing max.overlaps

names(results_list) <- sapply(pairs, function(x) paste(x, collapse = "_vs_"))

2.Statistical analysis

2.1 Univariate hypothesis

Research question : Do levels of LRRC15 differ across WHO temporary severity categories in patients with COVID-19.

Hypothesis : Patients with more severe COVID-19 have lower LRRC15 levels than patients with milder disease.

2.1.1 Anova test

Control criteria for Anova test

  • Normalization : Has been fixed

  • Independence : There are multiple measurement for each individual_ID

Solution for the multiple measurements for the same individual_ID:

library(dplyr)

df <- combined_log  # force reload correct object

protein_cols <- colnames(df)[2:(ncol(df)-17)]

# Make sure that idividual_id is not taking up in calculating the mean
protein_cols <- protein_cols[!protein_cols %in% c("individual_id", "WHO_temp_severity")]

# Group_by must use the exact column name
combined_mean <- df %>%
  group_by(individual_id, WHO_temp_severity) %>%
  summarise(
    across(all_of(protein_cols), mean, .names = "mean_{.col}"),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(new_individual_id = paste0(individual_id, "_", WHO_temp_severity)) %>%
  select(new_individual_id, individual_id, WHO_temp_severity, everything())

One-way anova:

# Filter out NEGATIVE category  
combined_filtered <- subset(combined_mean, WHO_temp_severity != "NEGATIVE")  
 
# One-way ANOVA on filtered data  
anova_result <- aov(mean_LRRC15 ~ WHO_temp_severity, data = combined_filtered)  
summary(anova_result)  
##                   Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)

Result : There is a significant difference between at least 2 different severity groups (p-value = 1.62e-06 ) To know between which groups there is a significant difference a Post-hoc Tukey test can be done :

# Post-hoc Tukey test  
tukey_result <- TukeyHSD(anova_result)

2.2 Multivariate hypothesis

Research question:Are lower LRRC15 levels, smoking, COPD and older age associated with case status?

hypothesis: Lower LRRC15 levels, smoking, COPD and older age are associated with a higher probability of being a case compared to a control.
